\section*{Question 1}
We can write $H$ in the following form by noting that $\pv=-i\hbar\grad$
\[H=c\boldsymbol{\alpha}\cdot\pv+mc^2\beta\]
\[\comm{H}{L}=(c\boldsymbol{\alpha}\cdot\pv+mc^2\beta)(\vb{r}\cp\pv)-(\vb{r}\cp\pv)(c\boldsymbol{\alpha}\cdot\pv+mc^2\beta)\]
Clearly $\comm{mc^2\beta}{\vb{r}\cp\pv}=0$ as $\beta$ is just a matrix of numbers. Now just consider the other part of the commutator ie
\[\frac{1}{c}\comm{H}{L}=\alpha_n p_n\epsilon_{ijk}r_j p_k-\epsilon_{ijk}r_j p_k \alpha_n p_n \]
\[=\m{0&\sigma_n\\\sigma_n&0}p_n\epsilon_{ijk}r_j p_k-\epsilon_{ijk}r_j p_k \m{0&\sigma_n\\\sigma_n&0} p_n \]
The Pauli matrices are complex two dimensional scalar matrices so they commute with one dimensional operators ie $\comm{r}{\sigma}=\comm{p}{\sigma}=0$. Hence we can again reduce this problem to solving
\[\frac{1}{c}\comm{H}{L}=\sigma_n p_n\epsilon_{ijk}r_j p_k-\epsilon_{ijk}r_j p_k \sigma_n p_n \]
Making use of $\comm{p_i}{r_j}=-i\hbar\delta_{ij}$ gives us
\[=\epsilon_{ijk}\big(\sigma_n(r_jp_n-i\hbar\delta_{nj})p_k-\sigma_nr_jp_kp_n\big)=\epsilon_{ijk}\big(\sigma_nr_jp_kp_n-i\hbar\delta_{nj}\sigma_np_k-\sigma_nr_jp_kp_n\big)  \]
Where we used that $\comm{p_i}{p_j}=0$
\[\therefore \ \comm{H}{L}=-i\hbar c\epsilon_{ink}\sigma_n p_k=-i\hbar c \sigmav\cp\pv\neq 0  \]
generally. So the $L$ operator doesn't commute with $H$. Suppose we pick an operator $S$... of course at COMPLETE RANDOM i.e $S=\frac{\hbar}{2}\sigma$. Does this now commute?
\[\comm{H}{L+S}=\comm{H}{L}+\comm{H}{S}\]
\[\comm{H}{S}=(c\boldsymbol{\alpha}\cdot\pv+mc^2\beta)\frac{\hbar}{2}\sigmav-\frac{\hbar}{2}\sigmav(c\boldsymbol{\alpha}\cdot\pv+mc^2\beta)  \]
Once again clearly $\comm{mc^2\beta}{S}=0$ so let's just focus on the other term. (Note we will replace $\alpha$ by $\sigma$ using the same logic as before)
\[\comm{H}{S}=\frac{\hbar c}{2}\bigg(\sigma_n p_n \sigma_m-\sigma_m\sigma_n p_n\bigg)\]
Using that $\sigma_n\sigma_m=\delta_{nm}+i\epsilon_{nmk}\sigma_k$ gives us
\[\frac{2}{\hbar c}\comm{H}{S}=(\delta_{nm}+i\epsilon_{nmk}\sigma_k)p_n-(\delta_{mn}+i\epsilon_{mnk}\sigma_k)p_n\]
\[=p_m+i\epsilon_{mkn}\sigma_k p_n-p_m-i(-\epsilon_{mkn})\sigma_k p_n=2i(\sigmav\cp\pv)  \]
\[\comm{H}{L+S}=-i\hbar c\sigmav\cp\pv+i\hbar c\sigmav\cp\pv=0\]
Hence we have found a spin operator that when added to $L$ commutes with the dirac Hamiltonian. \par
